</table></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ujochangaladar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jochan Galadar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Sage</span><br>  Posts: 607<br> <font color=#333333>(9/20/02 5:16:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=716.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Easy way to learn chain casting of pets...</span><hr size=1> My earliest experiences in chaincasting pets were in the Ocean of Tears.  I learned to meditate while the pet was fighting, and even though I was Spec Evocation at the time, I had more mana medded back up than I spent summoning the pet in the first place.<br>
<br>
Malachite usage varies by mob, but you can generally expect to go through 1-2 stacks an hour, or a little less.  This means as a $$ expense, it's no more than 4pp per hour at the most.<br>
<br>
Once you have the hang of chain casting pets, you can graduate to the next step at 59 and try reclaim chaining (train 3 points in Improved Reclaim first), which involves waiting for pet root to stick, reclaim, and resummon.  This tactic is by far our most mana efficient approach, and scales well with more magicians. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ukathartic.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kathartic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#333333>(9/20/02 5:29:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=716.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   learn chain casting</span><hr size=1> I only recently (at level 59) tried chain casting.  I found it to be a nice technique for soloing.   Sun revs on the plateau in SD is a very safe place to learn the technique as long as you keep lev up.   If anything goes wrong just run off the edge of the plateau.   Rev dies right away (no corpse or exp).  Invis and go back up and do it again.<br>
<br>
Also you can add some safety on exp mobs in many places by partnering with a Ranger.   Particularly one that needs to work on archery skill.  Summon up a bunch of arrows for him/her and you chain cast pets while the ranger drops in arrows for regular consistant damage.  Makes pets last longer, kills go faster and if you screw up (which will happen from time to time) you won't have to depend on channeling or root to save you.  Ranger can snare/root/kite/taunt/melee or whatever to give you a chance to get a new pet up<br>
<br>
Kathartic <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unaladini.showPublicProfile?language=EN>naladini</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 428<br> <font color=#333333>(9/20/02 6:04:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=716.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: learn chain casting</span><hr size=1> I've done it a few times now on tougher mobs, a few points/tips I've noticed:<br>
<br>
1) You're probably used to using a fully buffed and equipped pet. Once you start chaining, your subsequent pets won't last quite as long.<br>
<br>
2) Aggro management: Chaining is pretty straigtforward when soloing. However, it can be tricky to regain agro in a group setting if someone has been nuking a lot. Have expedience memmed so the pet can try catch the mob if a druid goes running. (It was one of those awkward situations where the pet got cursed and the heal spell from the druid didn't work).<br>
<br>
3) experiment with different types of pets during the chain. If you're in a group like above, maybe start with an Air Pet, but then chain an earth pet to help immobilize the mob. <p>Naladini <BR>
Elementalist of the 52nd Season-Stormhammer<BR>
